	(200,18,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(201,18,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Ex-internees who were permitted to leave the camps and return to their homes continued to face severe restriction on their freedoms following their release.  These restrictions were on top of the discriminatory policies and restrictions directed at members of ethnic minorities in Xinjiang in general (see chapter X above).\r\n\r\nMany survivors – particularly those interned in the early stages of the mass-incarceration campaign --- also reported witnessing dramatic changes in their villages, including the destruction or repurposing of mosques, shrines, and other cultural artifacts in their villages when they returned home (see section X above). [Pseudonym E1] told Amnesty what it was like when he see his village for the first time after being released from the camp. “They removed crescents from every mosque…. And from the furniture in homes. … Now every house had to have a picture of [President] Xi Jinping. Before we had a picture of a mosque,” he said.\r\n\r\nVariations of many of the restriction placed on ex-internees were also imposed on internees’ family during and after they were in the camp. [Pseudonym J2] worked with in the village administration why her family member was in a camp told Amnesty how a family member’s detention can affect the whole family.\r\n\r\n“When someone is sentence it affects three generations of the family. For example, if parents are sent [to a camp] then it affects son – he’s can’t get a job with government or police. … Also the cadres staying with [the family members of people in the camps] overnight had to report back to village committee if people prayed. And if they find this the [the family member in the camp’s] score will be lowered. … If person sent to a re-education camp, then family had to attend classes. If they do then family will get good score and get released sooner, or vice versa. We collect scores each week and sent to re-education camps.”\r\n\r\nPseudonym Q1] told Amnesty how found out how his family’s freedoms had been curtailed while he was in the camp.\r\n<blockquote>“While I was in camp, I thought my family had freedom, but I leaned that they were under house arrest. They had to ask permission to move… a cadre was consistently visiting house. … there was a camera in the street [in front of their house].”</blockquote>\r\nThe testimonial evidence provided to Amnesty is very consistent with testimonial evidence provided to other journalists and investigators as well as leaked government documents prescribing the treatment of ex-detainees during the months after their release, including the government directive that ex-detainees must be monitored one year.\r\n<blockquote>“Strengthen the work of follow-up help and education of the students, all local grassroots organizations are responsible for follow-up help and education, including police stations and the judicial office. Students must not leave the line of sight for one year and their performance should be grasped in a timely manner. It is necessary to strictly implement the responsibility of helping and educating and controlling, in order that not even one person leaks out, for comprehensive coverage.”</blockquote>'),
