	(459,27,'content_ml_rich_text_english','The majority of survivors interviewed by Amnesty were interrogated at police stations prior to being sent to a camp. A minority were sent directly to the camps without being interrogated. Most of the interrogations focused on questions about what the person had purportedly been arrested for (i.e. anything related to foreign countries, anything related to religion, and anything related to having illegal photos, videos, or software on your phone). Interrogations usually lasted several hours. Several people reported being extorted during the interrogations; they were told that if they paid money to the police then they would not be sent to a camp.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors reported being interrogated multiple times in police stations. The content of the interrogations in police stations was very similar to interrogations survivors went through inside the camps, and after their release. Many survivors described being asked the same questions over and over again by different govern officials, during multiple interrogations over the course of months and even years.\r\n\r\nMany of the survivors were tortured or otherwise ill-treated during interrogations in police stations before being transferred to the camps. Interrogations and torture were often carried out by members of the government security force known as Guobao, some were carried out by the local police. Survivors were often interrogated in Tiger chairs. Several were hooded and shackled during interrogations. According to [Pseudonym W1], who spent a year in the camps for visiting Kazakhstan, he was interrogation for several hours while  immobilized in tiger chair.\r\n<blockquote>“I was seated on a metal chair. Hands were cuffed. I was interrogated. My feet were also cuffed. … It’s a metal chair that contains a board that your hands are cuffed to. And there is an iron base that you put your legs inside. [The interrogation started late at night,] I was questioned until 3am.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym V1], who was arrested for going abroad, told Amnesty how he was repeatedly beaten and tased during interrogations.\r\n<blockquote>“They took me to the office [in the police station]. They took me into the interrogation room. …. There was a tiger chair in [the room]. It was made of steel. I sat on tiger chair and they gave me a notebook, and gave me half hour to write down everything that I did ... Then at 2am they started to beat me. Four of [police] had electric sticks. [All four] tased me until the batteries on the electric sticks died. … They were asking me about who met abroad.” [Pseudonym] was actually released after his interrogation, and was subsequently interrogated and tortured several more time before being sent to a camp.”</blockquote>\r\nMany survivors told Amnesty International that they were detained in crowded conditions prior to being sent to the camps. [Pseudonym F1] who held in a ‘detention center’ for three weeks before being transferred to a camp told Amnesty International that he was forced to stand in a small crowded cell with fifty other inmates all day. “We don’t even put cows in that terrible conditions. … we slept side by side touching each other,” he said.\r\n\r\nJournalists and other organizations have reported similar accounts of torture and ill-treatment, including beatings and sleep deprivation in police stations and detention centers.'),
