	(500,97,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(501,97,'content_ml_rich_text_english','<blockquote>“Classification management. In the training center, set up a strong (very strict) management area, a strict management area, and a general management area. According to the screening review, the trainees will be placed in one of the three management areas, and different education and training methods and management systems will be adopted accordingly. According to their actual performance and point situation, after evaluation and review, the student’s management and education classification can be dynamically adjusted.”\r\n– Classified Chinese government document – the ‘telegram’.</blockquote>\r\nShortly after arriving in the camp detainees are placed into one of three classification or categories. These categories reportedly correspond to the reasons they were detained and to the type of treatment they will be subjected to in the camp. The three categories were often referred to as ‘normal management’, ‘strict management’, and ‘very strict management’. This classification system is consistent with reporting from journalists, as well as the ‘Aksu’ and ‘Karakax’ lists, and other leaked government documents. Internees appear to have been placed in cells exclusively other internees in the same category.\r\n\r\nIn many – perhaps all -- of the camps, the category that a detainee was placed in corresponded to the colour of the uniform (or the badge ) they were given. Several survivors told Amnesty International that the least strict category were given blue uniforms, the strict category were given yellow (or orange), most strict category were given red.   The exact reason why specific internees are placed in different categories is not well understood. Several survivors said that the blue or normal group was for ‘ordinary’ crimes, such as having a prohibited application on your phone, that yellow was for any crimes related to religion, and that red was specifically for imams  or serious criminals. Other survivor  believe that the division was, at least in part, based on one ethnicity, as Uyghurs in their camps were much more likely to be in one of the two stricter categories. According to government documents – and survivor accounts -- it is possible for inmates to be moved from one category to another. Moreover, according to government documents, being assigned to the ‘least strict’ category may be a prerequisite for being released.\r\n\r\nWith two possible exceptions, the survivors interviewed by Amnesty International reported being placed in the category for those with the least severe crimes, the ‘normal management’ category. As a result, nearly all the conclusions made in this report come from testimonial evidence provided by survivors from the ‘normal management’ category alone. Like nearly all the testimonial evidence gathered about the camps from journalist and other organizations, the report provides very little information about the treatment of detainees in the other two categories. However, given the available evidence about the two stricter categories – which comes primarily from observations from survivors and staff who were in the same camps as internees in the stricter categories – it stands to reason the detainees in the stricter categories are treated much more severely and are much less likely to have been released from a camp and instead continued to be detained or have been transferred to a prison.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors stated that detainees were treated differently depending on which category they were placed in. [Pseudonym E2], who worked in the camps as a de facto staff member for part of the time that she was interned, told Amnesty International how she believed internees were categorized and how these categories corresponded to the types of treatment  received, especially with respect to their ability to move around the camp and to communicate with family members.\r\n\r\n“People were divided into three groups: ‘normal management’, ‘strict management’, and ‘very strict management’ Most of the people in the ‘strict management’ group are there for religious clerks or somehow involved with religion. … I know this because interrogations [or detainees] sometime took place in staff room where [I spent time] … [In the camp I worked in,] the ‘normal management’ group learned Chinese and were allowed to walk in the yard, the ‘strict  [management]’ [are allowed to] sit on their beds [some of the time], the very strict learn in their cell, are not allowed to move, and never get fresh air. … The normal group gets to make a call once a week and strict group once every two weeks and visits once a month. … The very strict group is not permitted to have visitors.”\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym], one of the two survivors Amnesty spoke with who may have been in the strict category, at least for part of his internment, was given a yellow uniform, for part of his stay. His offense – a religious based crime – and some of his treatment appears demonstrable worse that people in the normal management category. Notably, he was locked up for over two years, was not allowed to call family members when other detainees in his camp who were not detainees for religious crimes were, and, most notably, he was never allowed out of his cell and his feet were continuously shackled together for several months. “For two years, my family didn’t know if I was alive or dead,” [Pseudonym] told Amnesty international.'),
