	(519,29,'title',''),
	(520,29,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(521,29,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Every person deprived of liberty has the right to be held in conditions that are consistent with human dignity. This right is a norm of general international law: it applies at all times, in all circumstances, including in times of emergency. People deprived of their liberty must be held only in a place of detention that is officially recognized; states must ensure that no one is held secretly in prison.\r\n\r\nEveryone, including an individual in custody, has the right to the highest attainable standard of physical and mental health. The right to health extends not only to timely and appropriate health care, but also to underlying determinants of health, such as adequate food, water and sanitation. As well as fresh air, natural light, and access to some form of exercise. Cramped and unhygienic accommodation and lack of privacy in custody can amount to inhuman or degrading treatment. Law enforcement officials and prison authorities are responsible for protecting the health of people in their custody. The failure to provide access to adequate health care has been held to violate the rights to respect for dignity and health as well as the prohibition of inhuman or degrading treatment.\r\n\r\nDetained and imprisoned people have a right to communicate with the outside world, subject only to reasonable conditions and restrictions that are proportionate to a legitimate aim. Detention without access to the outside world – incommunicado detention – facilitates torture or other ill-treatment and enforced disappearance. Depending on the circumstances, it can itself constitute torture or other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.'),
