	(562,98,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(563,98,'content_ml_rich_text_english','An internees’ day beings at five or six in the morning. Internees are woken up from an alarm through the loudspeaker or from a loud knock on the cell door. Then they must quickly wash up, either inside the cell or by crawling under the chain attaching the cell door to the wall and then being escorted to the washroom by a guard. Washing up usually consists of brushing your teeth and washing your face in a sink. Some detainees were permitted to shower approximately once a week; others reported not being permitted to shower for weeks or months after they arrived.'),
