	(693,104,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(694,104,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Three survivors told Amnesty International that they were not interned in a formal ‘camp’, but instead spent the majority of their internment detained in hospitals. This included two elderly survivors who were kept inside hospital rooms for nearly a year with several other elderly detainees. They were nominally told to ‘learn’ mandarin, but both reported essentially just sitting in the room for months on end.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym S1], an elderly woman, how she spent most of her detention in room in hospital with older elderly woman, none of whom were permitted to leave the floor.\r\n<blockquote>“I was at the hospital the whole summer… it is the [top] floor of a normal hospital, but it is blocked from other floors, and the windows are barred, only doctors can come in and out …I was kept in a room with six other elderly people. … we were not allowed to go outside. …  We spent most of the day just sitting on our bed. … We had lessons but I had problems hearing and my eyes were bad; they didn’t pressure me. The just demanded that I sign my name in Chinese… and we had to sing red songs.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym S1] also told Amnesty International how her children we made to pay for her stay at the hospital.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym Y1], an elderly woman, was also kept in a hospital room with a group of elderly woman for several months. She told Amnesty how they spent the time.\r\n<blockquote>“[During the day] we would wake up and have breakfast in the room. We were handed papers and books. I pretended to read, but I didn’t understand anything. We would pretend to learn all day. Then we would have a meal and to sleep. They taught some ‘red’ songs. They wanted us to learn Chinese words. We weren’t allowed out. We just wanted to be released. We were only allowed to go to the toilet. Otherwise we stayed in the room.”</blockquote>'),
	(695,104,'_content_ml_rich_text_english','field_5edfa91e024b0'),
