	(705,35,'title_ml_text_english','Language Training'),
	(706,35,'_title_ml_text_english','field_5edfa7bf9ba7d'),
	(707,35,'title_ml_text_chinese',''),
	(708,35,'_title_ml_text_chinese','field_5edfa7989ba7c'),
	(709,35,'title_ml_text_uyghur',''),
	(710,35,'_title_ml_text_uyghur','field_602658467ef5f'),
	(711,35,'title_ml_text',''),
	(712,35,'_title_ml_text','field_5edfa76c9ba7b'),
	(713,35,'title',''),
	(714,35,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(715,35,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Teaching Mandarin was a primary objective of the ‘re-education’. Speaking in any other language was forbidden and a punishable offense. Language classes take up the majority of the time in a day. Nearly all survivors reported having to regularly pass language exams and being required to learn a certain number - often ‘3000’ - Chinese characters before being released. This is consistent with leaked government documents which stipulate regular examinations and that tests score “will be aggregated to form study points, which are used to evaluate the effect of the education and training and form the main basis to determine whether a student has completed (their course).”\r\n\r\nInmates who fail to memorize words or songs often received physical punishments. “We were under pressure to learn 3000 characters. There were many exams. I graduated high school and it was hard for me. It was very hard for old people, and for farmers,” [Pseudonym D1] told Amnesty International.\r\n\r\nDetainees were sometimes divided according to their language abilities; however, many survivors who spoke fluent mandarin reported being forced to sit in basic classes and many survivors who did not speak any mandarin reported not understanding anything that was being said in class for months. Many detainees expressed difficultly with the classes. “The classes were mainly Chinese language but it wasn’t helpful. Each day they just wrote 100s of characters on the board. We just copied. No one tried to explain,” [Pseudonym] told Amnesty International.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym], who spend a year in the camp for visiting Kazakhstan and for an offense related to religion, told Amnesty how the language classes involved rote memorization.\r\n<blockquote>“During the class there is a Han teacher who writes Chinese characters on a board and we just copy it without knowing what it was. That was it. We just write characters. … It was just language… we were not allowed to speak Uyghur in class. If you do [speak a language other than Mandarin] you get punished. You are taken to a room with tiger chair… I was taken twice.”</blockquote>\r\nThe survivors accounts of language classes is consistent with testimony given my other survivors. And from leaked government documents.'),
	(716,35,'_content_ml_rich_text_english','field_5edfa91e024b0'),
	(717,35,'content_ml_rich_text_chinese',''),
	(718,35,'_content_ml_rich_text_chinese','field_5edfa91e0243c'),
