	(767,107,'_edit_last','1'),
	(768,107,'_edit_lock','1613383319:1'),
	(769,107,'title_ml_text_english','‘Class’'),
	(770,107,'_title_ml_text_english','field_5edfa7bf9ba7d'),
	(771,107,'title_ml_text_chinese',''),
	(772,107,'_title_ml_text_chinese','field_5edfa7989ba7c'),
	(773,107,'title_ml_text_uyghur',''),
	(774,107,'_title_ml_text_uyghur','field_602658467ef5f'),
	(775,107,'title_ml_text',''),
	(776,107,'_title_ml_text','field_5edfa76c9ba7b'),
	(777,107,'title',''),
	(778,107,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(779,107,'content_ml_rich_text_english','At some point after arriving in the camp, nearly all survivors reported being subjected to highly regimented classes – either in-person or via video lectures or both. The classes were mostly about Chinese language, history, law, and ‘ideology’. Some involved memorizing and reciting ‘red’ songs. The typical schedule includes three or four hours of class after breakfast. Then lunch. Then a short ‘rest’, which often involved sitting still on your stool or with you head still on your desk. After lunch there is another three or four hours of class. Then dinner. Then a few hours to sit or kneel on your stool and silently ‘review’ the days’ material or to watch more ‘educational’ videos. At nearly all times during class, internees are required to look straight ahead and not to speak with their classmates.\r\n\r\nClasses are usually held in classroom outside of the cells. Inmates from two or more cells are regularly brought together in one larger class, with approximately 50 people. Although several survivors reported having classes in their cell.\r\n\r\nInternees would often have to line up or sit and wait for hours in the morning, because of the logistical constraints of transferred the thousands of people from cells to classroom. [Pseudonym], told Amnesty that he spent a large portion of the day waiting to be escorted to class:\r\n<blockquote>“After classes started, we got moving at 6am. It took 2-3 hours to send all inmates to class. The class was one kilometer away. The cage line, beginning from dorm to class is really narrow, we can only walk single file. Take 2-3 hours for everyone to get there.”</blockquote>\r\nWhile walking to the classroom – or to anywhere else in the camp – internees have to walk inside of yellow lines that are painted on the ground of the facility. Anyone who stepped on or over the lines risks physical punished.   [Pseudonym X6], who had been sent to a camp because she refused to work for government, told Amnesty that she remembered a staff member speaking about the two yellow lines on the floor of the camp: “he said: ‘You people went outside of the path. [In this camp] you will learn to go inside the path.”\r\n\r\nInternees are escorted to class by guards. Some guards have shields and electric batons. When travelling from the cell to the classroom, internees sometime walk ‘outside’ to another, but were almost always under some sort of caged enclosure. “The road from the dorm to classroom were surrounded by wires and armed guard who looked like they were ready to shoot you,” [Pseudonym] told Amnesty International. Internees were often required to march to the class in a military-type formation, shouting slogans. [Pseudonym M2] told Amnesty that inmates were required to march to and from class ‘like soldiers’ and that while marching they were required to shout: “study hard, elevate yourself, eliminate separatist forces, and long live Xi Jinping!”\r\n\r\nThe teacher and guards enter the classroom using one door. And the students enter through another, which, like the cell doors, is chained to the wall. Guards are stationed inside or immediately outside the classroom. Classes begin and end with the class thanking the teacher for their sacrifice.\r\n\r\nStudents and teachers are physically separated at all times. Classrooms have a hard plastic, wooden, or metal divider, usually just over a meter high,  which separates the students and the teacher/guards. There is often a wire or metal net in the space above the divider. Desks and stools in the class are often chained together. Several survivors reported being given short pencils to write with, or the plastic tube with the ink and tip from inside a ‘bic’ type pen, presumably because a full-seize pencil or a pen could be used as a weapon. [Pseudonym W2] described his experience in the classroom to Amnesty International:\r\n<blockquote>“Every day was almost the same. … We are brought to a place where you have to sit for seventeen hours. It was in another room in the same building. [In the classroom] there are five or six armed guards and a teacher. The door to class is also chained, you must crawl to get in. … The teacher is behind a barrier, [the barrier] is maybe neck height. You can see them but you can’t cross [the barrier]. The guards are on the teacher’s side.  They taught us verses from Confucius. We had to read [the verses] out loud and repeat them hundreds of times. And there were loudspeakers in the classroom. Several times I heard [a voice on the loudspeaker saying] ‘give more pressure’.”</blockquote>\r\nInternees were made to sit absolutely straight while at their desks. Survivors reported people being taken out  of class and beaten or punished if they did not sit straight and look straight ahead. [Pseudonym M2] told Amnesty International that failure to sit straight could also affect an internee’s ‘score’.\r\n<blockquote>“We had to sit straight with our hand behind our back. In our classroom, there were old woman. Their hand and feet swell up. If you miss your home , if you cry, they will deduct from you score – they give scores to everyone – and they will say that your mind still has problems, that your ideas didn’t change.”</blockquote>\r\nInclude teacher accounts.'),
