	(838,40,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(839,40,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Amnesty International interviewed XX women and XX men who were tortured or subjected to other ill-treatment during interrogations or punishments in internment camps in Xinjiang between 2017 and 2019. Amnesty International also interviewed XX woman and XX men who either witnessed the torture other ill-treatment of other detainees, or spoke with other detainees – usually their cellmates – who informed them that they had been tortured or otherwise ill-treated during interrogations or as punishment.\r\n\r\nTorture methods included beatings, electric shocks, stress position, the unlawful use of restraints, including being locked to a tiger chair, sleep deprivation, being hung from the wall, and being subjected to extremely cold temperatures. Amnesty International documented once account of a killing in an internment camp that was caused by torture.\r\n\r\nSurvivors and witnesses described a broadly consistent pattern of treatment of detainees by Chinese security forces. Some of this reflects patterns of torture and other ill-treatment that have been carried out by Chinese security forces in Xinjiang and other parts of China for decades. According to survivors, the torture and other ill-treatment was carried out both by camp guards and by members of Guoboa who came to the camps for the purposes of interrogating detainees.\r\n\r\nTorture and other ill-treatment usually took place in interrogation or ‘punishment’ rooms. These rooms are usually windowless and contain at least one ‘tiger chair’, which is used for the interrogations. A few survivors reported being interrogated in rooms with multiple tiger chairs.'),
