	(897,110,'title_ml_text_chinese',''),
	(898,110,'_title_ml_text_chinese','field_5edfa7989ba7c'),
	(899,110,'title_ml_text_uyghur',''),
	(900,110,'_title_ml_text_uyghur','field_602658467ef5f'),
	(901,110,'title_ml_text',''),
	(902,110,'_title_ml_text','field_5edfa76c9ba7b'),
	(903,110,'title',''),
	(904,110,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(905,110,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Physical Ill-treatment takes place throughout the camps, most commonly through beatings. Detainees who misbehave – even for the most trivial of offenses -- are also routinely beaten by guards. Amnesty International interviewed XX people who reported being beaten during detention. Including X woman. Electric batons were often used. Numerous survivors witnessed others internees being beaten.Including older internees. [Pseudonym H2] a guard worked in a camp, told Amnesty International that internees were regularly beaten in his camp. ‘”Everyday someone is taken out {of the class] and beaten, with hands, feet, weapons and baton,” he said.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym C2] told Amnesty how he was beaten shortly after arriving the camp when he resisted being strip-searched by guards:\r\n<blockquote>“When I said I wouldn’t take off my underwear they beat be with an electric stick. And I then I fell. They beat me and I was electrocuted. … when I can to my senses, they took off my clothes, they searched me, made me bend down, tied hand behind neck. It was very painful.”</blockquote>\r\nNumerous detainees and one former internment camp guard told Amnesty that people were routinely beaten if they did not learn appropriately during classes. [Pseudonym X8] told Amnesty how guards routinely beat people as they walked to class and how a man in his class was taken out of class beaten for not signing a song properly.\r\n<blockquote>“The guards would always beat people while walking to class… [name redacted] was beaten, he was an ethnic Uzbek, a Han Chinese [guard] beat him and put him in isolation for 24 hours… he came back with bruises. I was in his cell… and [the guard] would call people who couldn’t recite Chinese content to the door [then the person who was call would stick their hand through hole in the door] and then cuff them to the door and beat them with an electric baton… I saw [people being beaten] 2-3 times… I could hear it [happening] in hall many more times.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym X9] was beaten by guards because he questioned an order, and then severely beaten after he tried to fight back.\r\n<blockquote>“[One of the guards] said ‘squat and put your hands on the back of your head!’ … I asked why. Then the police hit me with the back of a rifle. … I wanted to protect myself so I hit back. He fell down. Then the other police all hit me. Why I was being beaten up I heard one voice saying ‘end him with one bullet’ ... I thought I was going to die. … I wanted not to be killed and I scream… then they sprayed something in my eyes.”</blockquote>\r\nThese types of beating during interrogations have been widely reported by other detainees interviewed by journalists and other human rights organizations.'),
