	(926,111,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(927,111,'content_ml_rich_text_english','A few survivors reported being shackled on their legs for much or all of their time in detention. One survivor, who also worked in an internment camp, told Amnesty that all detainees in the ‘strict’ and ‘most strict’ sections in the camp she worked in had to be shackled at all times.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym E1] told Amnesty international that his feet were shackled together for the first year he was in a camp.\r\n<blockquote>“It was a metal chain with 11 circles. The two ends on feet with bolts. [It weighed about] 3kg. We could barely walk 20cm or more. I could barely walk. It was on 24/7. Every week the guards would check chain. Every two weeks they would tighten the bolts. … [Several months after I arrived in the camp] they offered us water for showering, but always with the chain on. The old inmates showed us how to take pants off. We took our pants off through the space between the chain and ankle, but it takes a really long time.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym A3] told Amnesty how he saw immobilized people tortured through exposure to the cold while walk from his cell to the medical clinic in the camp.\r\n<blockquote>“I saw how they torture [other people]. One time the set a young lady in metal chair outside [in January] in thin clothes… [I saw] seven Uyghur men and handcuffed [outside]to metal bars and chain on their feet without shoes.”</blockquote>'),
