	(1083,118,'title',''),
	(1084,118,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1085,118,'content_ml_rich_text_english','Prior to being released nearly all the survivors interviewed by Amnesty International were interrogated by government officials, often by three or four different groups of officials from different government bodies. During these interrogations, internees were asked about religious practice, contacts abroad, and the other things they had been questioned about repeatedly before and during their internment. Internees were also usually required to confess to their crimes, to recognize that their past behavior was wrong, to swear that they would not act that way again, to talk about how much they appreciated the education they had received, and to explain how their thoughts had been ‘transformed’. Several survivors had to disavow their religion as a condition of their release. Several survivors also said that their family and friends were questioned before they were released and that their family members had to fill out a long questionnaire. The accounts of the release process given to Amnesty are consistent with accounts leaked government documents, as well as from accounts that other survivors have provided to journalists.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym X15] who was in the camp for a year before being released remembered multiple officials reviewing her documents in front of her and then giving her a score.  [Pseudonym X18] told Amnesty that during the weeks prior to his release he was interviewed by four different groups of government officials – ‘school’ level, county level, prefecture level, autonomous region level – and that he was required to sign a document saying that he wouldn’t practice Islam after he was released.\r\n<blockquote>“All the [interrogations] were the same. [They asked] ‘What did you learn? Have your thoughts transformed? Do you love China? What are you going to do when you are released? Do you appreciate your re-education?’ We had to answer all the questions positively or be sent to jail. We know this. … Each [interrogation] was 1-2 weeks apart, and was for 30-60 minutes. … When they [arrested] us they made up one reason [for our arrest] even though we didn’t do it. … [Before you are released] you have write something. [You have to start what you write] with that reason. Then you copy a form saying you won’t pray, won’t go to a mosque, and will follow all Chinese laws.”</blockquote>\r\nEveryone who is released is forced to swear in writing not to disclosure anything about their detention to anyone, including to members of their family, and especially not to foreigners. Everyone is told that if they do disclose information about the camps they will be interned again or sent to prison, potentially along with members of their family. Some survivors were told to deny that they had ever been to a camp.\r\n\r\nAccording to [Pseudonym J2], who work worked in a village administration office while he family member was in a camp, family members of about-to-be-released internees also receive a call from government officials warning them not to disclose that their family member had been to camp, and were threatened with jail time if journalists every found out anything about their family members internment.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym O1] told Amnesty how he told he would be sent back to the camp for a third time if he told anything about the camps.\r\n<blockquote>“I spent eight months in the camp [the second time]. … The day I was released I had to sign many documents saying that I wouldn’t say anything I saw in the facility. I signed and then they started calling us for interrogation. During the interrogation they told us not to disclose anything that I saw in school and if I did that I would be taken back.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym I1] told Amnesty International how he was required to write a letter of gratitude to the party before being released.\r\n<blockquote>“[During the final time I was interrogated in the camp], a few days before I was released, I had to write down everything that happened to me in a foreign country. And to write about communism and democracy. I knew that we had to praise communism and despise democracy so that is what I did. And I had to write that if I ever spoke about what happened in jail then my parents would be sentences. Then I had to sign and put my fingerprint on the paper.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym I2] told Amnesty International how she had to write a gratitude letter and sign a confession letter and many other documents before being released.\r\n<blockquote>“Before I was released I had to write a letter of gratitude to the party, thanking them for feeding and educating us. And I had to write a confession letter, saying that I committed a mistake by going to Kazakhstan, and that I must have also come across someone in Kazakhstan… you needed three letters to sign out. [The third] said not allowed to say anything about what experience in the camp and that if you do then you agree to be judged and sent back to the camp.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym F1] told Amnesty International how, he was made to sign a confession before he was released – along with 50 other people from his village, all of who were Kazakhs.\r\n<blockquote>“I was accused of being a religious extremist and going to Kazakhstan, I signed [the confession] …. Two days before we were released they told us that they would be releasing us, but that if we told anything [ about the camps] then we would be sent back here, even our wives [would be sent back].”</blockquote>\r\nAccording to [Pseudonym F1] after he was released people in the ‘strict management’ group in his camp were sentenced to prison.\r\n\r\nSeveral survivors said that they were coached on what to say to friends and relatives after they were released. [Pseudonym Z1] told Amnesty International that prior to her release she was brought to a police station, where they put make up on her and fed her. She was interrogated repeatedly over the course of a week, during which time they also told her what to do for video they wanted her to make.\r\n<blockquote>“[Before I could be released] I had to make a video saying good things about the CPP and what they had done for me, and how strong the country was, and that the World Uyghur Congress did terrorist activities, and the president of the World Uyghur Congress is bad.”</blockquote>'),
