	(1167,48,'title',''),
	(1168,48,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1169,48,'content_ml_rich_text_english','A portion of the internees – who are not released and not sent to forced labour situation – are given prison sentences and transferred to prisons. The total number of people who have been transferred from camps to prisons is not known. An analysis of official data by the New York Times showed a record surge in arrests, trials and prison sentences in Xinjiang between 2017 and 2018. According to the data, approximately 230000 individuals were ‘sentenced’ in Xinjiang in 2017 and 2018, a ten- to twenty-fold increase from previous years.  The data reportedly includes prison sentences and “other criminal punishments, which can include suspended sentences or house detention.” In 2017 alone, prison sentences over five years increased ten-fold from the previous years to nearly 87,000. The data does not reveal whether it includes people who are given prison sentences while in internment camps. Some scholars have argued that a large percentage – perhaps most -- of those who are ‘released’ from a camp and not sent to a factory or some other form of forced labour have been sent prisons. Journalists have reported that large number of people have transferred to prisoners in inner China.\r\n\r\nThere is almost no first hand testimony from anyone sent to a camp and then sentence to prison while they are in the camp. However, there is second-hand testimony that suggests that the reason for one’s arrest appears to be a factor, with people in prison for religious-related ‘crimes’ more likely to be sentenced. Numerous survivors told Amnesty that those internees who they knew in their classes and camps who were sent for religious offenses were less likely to be released. Many also reported that Uyghurs were much less likely to be released than Kazakhs. Most of the Kazakh survivors said that the vast majority of the people released from their camps were Kazakh, not Uyghur, even though Uyghurs made up the overwhelming majority of the camp populations. [Pseudonym] told Amnesty that nearly all the Kazakh people were released from his camp “I was one of the last [Kazakhs] in the camp because [I was in the camp for a reason related to religion].”\r\n\r\nThe process through which prison sentences are determined is also not well understood. At some point during an internee’s time in the camp they are provided with a ‘verdict’ that lists their crimes and often includes a sentence. Several survivors said the verdicts were given at end of a process referred to as a ‘trial’. However, no survivors experienced anything that resembled a fair legal or even administrative process. The was no opportunity to defend themselves, examine the evidence, or to consult with a lawyer. Some survivors didn’t recall any real ‘process’ before they received a verdict and said that their verdicts and the verdicts of their classmate were just read out in class.\r\n\r\nNot everyone who receives a guilty verdict is sent to prison. It appears that some ‘sentences’ are expected to be served in the camp. Two survivors told Amnesty that people with verdicts under ten years were to be served in the camp, people with verdicts over ten years were sent to prison. It is also plausible that some verdicts are initially provided as scare tactics or that they can be altered with good behaviours. All of the survivors interviewed by Amnesty were given ‘guilty’ verdicts, and a few were given prison ‘sentences’; however, those sentences were rescinded and none of the survivors interviewed by Amnesty International was sent to prison.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym] who was in the camp for refusing to work for the government, told Amnesty International that they started giving verdicts to people in her class several months after she arrived in the camp. “ [Mine said] that I deserve 5-10 years, but that the government is merciful so I don’t need to go to prison… they said that my sin was going to a country that was on the sensitive country list and not cooperating with neighbourhood committee.” [Pseudonym] was subsequently released after an appeal from family members abroad.\r\n\r\nAmnesty International interviewed XX survivors said that while they were detained one or more of the people in their class received prison sentences.  Included several for twenty years. [Pseudonym T1] told Amnesty International how he was taken to a ‘court’, which involved him answering questions – similar to what he had done in previous interrogations. He was not given a sentence but many of his cell mates were.\r\n<blockquote>“A month or so before I was released, people were taken to ‘court’ rooms and given sentences… [I was taken to the ’court’ room] they just asked me what I had done. … I said I had been to Kazakhstan. … She said you need more time here. [She] didn’t give me a sentence… If I’m not mistaken she was a Uyghur. She had a list of questions ... I was good at answering… it was just the two of us, talking in Uyghur. … She already had documents about me in front of her. …  Everyone [in my cell] went to court. Some came back [to the cell] and said they got prison terms. Some were the same as me [and were not given any sentence]. … Some of those who did [get sentenced] were then [moved out of the cell]”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym E1], who was one of the few survivors who was temporarily placed in the ‘strict’ category and given a yellow badge said that about a year into his time in the camp, several of his cell mates, were taken to ‘court’ and given sentences. “They took people to ‘court.’  A few days later [those people] get verdicts. The staff in charge [or our cell] comes to cell and reads the verdict. We can hear it read,” he said. [Pseudonym E1] provided amnesty with the full names of two of his cell mates who were sentences, and said that one was given 15 years for gathering with other and reading a book about religion and the another was five 7.5 years for insulting the police and country leaders.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym X9], who spent nearly a year and a half in different camps, told Amnesty International that he was in a class of 50, which was approximately half Uyghur and half Kazakhs and Dungans. He said that all of the Uyghurs, five Dungans, and two Kazakhs were given sentences. “They would read verdicts in class. … [one man received] ‘3 years for going to halal restaurant’ … [another man received] ‘7 years for you having camping equipment or boxing [equipment], because then you were involved in terrorism,” he said.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym D1] told Amnesty that people who received sentences of 10 years or more were sent directly to prison, and that three men from his class – two Uyghurs and one Kazakh, were sent to prison. He said he was told this secretly by staff in the camp. “Those verdicts over ten years are directly sent to prison, family gets verdict. Those teachers in camp, they talk secretly to us [and tell us that people went sent to prison],” he said.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym], who was sent to a camp because of his involvement with his local mosque, told Amnesty that one day while in class people were called one-by-one to another room and told what their verdict was.\r\n<blockquote>“People who were religious got [between] two and ten-year prison terms. The person who was imam in mosque in my village was given a seven-year sentence [his name is…] ... he told me about the sentence. We were in the same room. … Initially I was given 3-7 years but then they forgave me and I wasn’t given a prison term. … They didn’t explain why. Maybe because [a relative] did an appeal for [my release] from Kazakhstan.”</blockquote>'),
