	(1233,125,'title',''),
	(1234,125,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1235,125,'content_ml_rich_text_english','All survivors faced significant restriction on their freedom of movement after they were released from the camp. Nearly everyone was prohibited from leaving their village or their township, or if they were allowed to leave they were required to get written permission from the authorities beforehand.   Several were essentially put under house arrest. Many survivors were required to check-in with the police or village administrators on a daily basis. Several were forced to live at the village administration office or police station for few week or months. [Pseudonym D1] told Amnesty how he movements were restricted after he was released. “I spent five months being monitored. I just stayed in village. I couldn’t leave without permission. I had to report to the village [administration] office each morning. I needed permission to leave village from the village chief,” he said.\r\n\r\nMany survivors reported that for months after they left the camp that their ID cards were programmed such that an alarm would go off whenever they travel through checkpoints, or whenever they left their village.   When IDs triggered an alarm ex-internees were often interrogated about the very same ‘issues’ they were questioned about after their arrest and during their detention [Pseudonym X11], a woman her fifties who had been detained for a year for visiting Kazakhstan, told Amnesty International how her movement was restricted after she was released from the camps.\r\n<blockquote>“After I was released… it was house arrest. Every time I scanned my ID it went off … I wasn’t allowed to go to another town. Even in the streets, the camp follows you… Even when I went to buy a meal I had to fill in a form saying I had been to a camp. It was shameful… my daughter was living [in another town] I couldn’t visit her because of this. Can you imagine going into the street and the police surround you every time.”</blockquote>\r\nOther detainees told Amnesty that their ID was confiscated for a time after their released. “[When I wasn’t in class or at a flag raising ceremony] I had to stay at home the rest of the time, because the inspector could come at any time. I had to be found in one of these places at all time. My ID was taken. I wasn’t free,” [Pseudonym M1] told Amnesty International.\r\n\r\nIt appears that after several months many of the victims some of the movement restrictions begin to decrease. Many reported that some restriction were lifted after six months. Several survivors told Amnesty that the restriction on their movements lasted for a year. One survivor told Amnesty that the restrictions on his movement were removed at the same time as others released when he was. [Pseudonym] told Amnesty that he was placed under house arrest after leave the camp, which was lifted after three months.\r\n<blockquote>“After three month [under house arrest] I was told that with permission I could visit other villages, but before I had to visit the village administration and the police station to get stamps and then they would give my ID and documents that I needed to show with ID to go through the checkpoints.”</blockquote>\r\nThe family member of internees also had severe restrictions placed on them while their family members were in the camps. Several survivors report that their family members needed to get permission from local officials to leave their village.'),
