	(1291,128,'title_ml_text_english','Restrictions on leaving the country and treatment of those abroad who are abroad'),
	(1292,128,'_title_ml_text_english','field_5edfa7bf9ba7d'),
	(1293,128,'title_ml_text_chinese',''),
	(1294,128,'_title_ml_text_chinese','field_5edfa7989ba7c'),
	(1295,128,'title_ml_text_uyghur',''),
	(1296,128,'_title_ml_text_uyghur','field_602658467ef5f'),
	(1297,128,'title_ml_text',''),
	(1298,128,'_title_ml_text','field_5edfa76c9ba7b'),
	(1299,128,'title',''),
	(1300,128,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1301,128,'content_ml_rich_text_english','It has been difficult for minorities in Xinjiang to travel abroad for years. The restriction became more severe in 2015 and 2016 when ethnic minorities were requested to hand in their passports. Since 2017, it has been nearly impossible for Uyghurs to leave the country. And sometime forbidden for them to leave their villages. The few who have gotten out having ties to foreign countries and after international pressure or bribes.\r\n\r\nKazakhs have also been restricted; however, after the intervention of the government of Kazakhstan, some Kazakhs with Kazakhstani citizenship or strong family ties to Kazakhstan have been able to leave china. Before leaving there is Sisyphean bureaucratic process to get the approvals to get your passport back and to secure getting permission to go abroad. And for ex-detainees there is a further round of interrogations by security forces, and you always have to sign additional documents saying that you won’t say anything or your family members will be sent to camp.\r\n\r\nSeveral detainees were even forced to give video testimonies prior to leaving the country. [Pseudonym] who spent several months trying to secure permission to travel to Kazakhstan told Amnesty International that he was forced to make a video extol the benefits of the education he received in the camp before he was allowed to leave.\r\n<blockquote>“One week [after I got my passport back], people from DADUI called me again. Then they took my passport again and said they would keep it until county level official signed [the form]. And then they gave me a piece of paper to sign saying I would not disclose anything about the camp or the secrets of the republic of china, and I signed it. I made an oath that I would not disclose. … After I signed, 3-4 cadres came to my house. They came with cameras. Before they started filming they told me what to say – that I went to school and that I got knowledge and that I was happy with government and the opportunity to gain knowledge. … In front of camera I said that the party is taking good care of and that the government is helping the poor people… and that during the 7-8 months of my school the teacher and others were friendly and the taught me well. … I was instructed to say this so I said it. They saved the tape. They repeated to me not to say anything bad. Then I signed the paper where I said I would. Then they gave me my passport back. [Then I left the country].</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym] told Amnesty that he was interrogated several times while trying to get passports for his family to go to Kazakhstan. He was repeatedly told by security officials that I could not talk about what happened in the camps. And that he has to swear on video that he would never disclose anything about the situation. He parents were also required to sign guarantor letters before her. “My parents had to say: ‘I do give my consent and I will be taken to a camp, if my son ever speaks to foreign media and discloses what happened in camp’,” he told Amnesty International. Several months later his family was given their passports.\r\n\r\nMany camp survivors also told Amnesty International that regaining their freedom of movement – to travel abroad and, in some cases, to travel within China outside of their home village – was contingent upon having one or more ‘guarantors’ who agreed in writing that they would be sent to a camp if the person they were guaranteeing spoke or shared information about the internment camp system.  Old woman needed many guarantors to leave.'),
