	(1608,31,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1609,31,'content_ml_rich_text_english','The life of an internee is extraordinarily highly regimented. With the exception of a few survivors describing the portion of their detention that took place in early 2017, every internee stated that nearly every minute of their lives in the camp was proscribed, including the position in which they sat, when they stood, and where they looked. From the moment the detainees entered the camp, they are essentially stripped of their autonomy – physically and, to a large extent, mentally -- and every aspect of their lives is dictated to them. Deviations from the schedule or the ‘rules’ – even for the most seemingly innocuous of behaviors – are reprimanded and often punished. The detainees are monitored at all times, including when they sleep, eat, ‘study’, and use the toilet. If anyone in the cell ‘misbehaves’, they are shouted at by the staff monitoring them on the cameras or sent to ‘punishment room’.\r\n\r\n[Pseudonym], who was detained in early 2017 because he was labelled ‘terrorist’ for travelling to Kazakhstan and for having attended a religious school, told Amnesty International how the daily regimentation became much stricter in late 2017, to the point where even ‘resting’ was regulated:\r\n<blockquote>“Before October 2017, it was a little relaxing in class. We could go to the canteen [to eat] by ourselves and we could sit relaxed in class. But after the national [security] meeting in October [2017] it became very serious. … We had to be ‘on duty’ at night [monitoring our cell mates]. We were escorted to the canteen. We had no more contact with our family. … We must ‘sit tight’. We cannot even turn our heads from the TV. … [After it became strict] We got up at 5am. Breakfast was done at 7. Class at 8. We have to [walk] to class through a two-meter high metal fence with metal ceiling; it was basically a cage … [we are escorted] to class by two guards with clubs. … There is a bucket in the back of class [to urinate]. You needed permission to go [defecate]. … Rest [after lunch] was mandatory, with heads on desk for two hours. You were punished if you lifted your head.”</blockquote>\r\n[Pseudonym], who was detained in the camp for X months for having WhatsApp on her phone, told Amnesty international how the physically draining each day was.\r\n<blockquote>“It was like a prison. … [Every day] you get up at 5am and have to make your bed, and it had to be perfect. Then there was a flag raising ceremony and an ‘oath taking’. Then you went to the canteen for breakfast. Then to the classroom. Then lunch. Then to the classroom. Then dinner. Then another class. Then bed. Every night two people had to be ‘on duty’ for 2 hours. …. There was not a minute left for yourself. You are exhausted.”</blockquote>'),
