	(1628,32,'_title','field_602657cc293e7'),
	(1629,32,'content_ml_rich_text_english','The government of China has referred to the internment camps as ‘vocational training centers’ or ‘re-education camps’. And the part of an internee’s day that isn’t spent eating or sleeping – usually twelve hours – is devoted to so-called ‘re-education’. The ‘re-education’ in the camp is normally delivered via lectures in classroom. However, in many cases, formal classes did not begin until an internee had been at a camp for several weeks, and often not for several months.'),
